  "prompt": "Why am I allergic to dogs and not to cats?",
  "response": "Allergic reactions to pets are typically caused by proteins found in their skin cells (dander), urine, and saliva. The reasons you might be allergic to dogs but not to cats could be due to several factors:\n\n1. **Allergen Proteins**: Dogs and cats produce different types of allergens. The proteins that trigger allergic reactions in dogs can differ from those in cats. You may be sensitive to specific dog allergens but not to those produced by cats.\n\n2. **Exposure Levels**: Your level of exposure to each pet can also influence your allergic reactions. If you've been around dogs more than cats, you may have developed an allergy to dog allergens simply due to increased exposure.\n\n3. **Individual Sensitivity**: Each person's immune system reacts differently to various allergens. It's possible to have individual sensitivities that make you allergic to one species but not the other.\n\n4. **Breeds**: Certain dog breeds are known to produce fewer allergens than others. If you have only been exposed to certain breeds, that could affect your reaction.\n\n5. **Environmental Factors**: Other factors such as your environment, the presence of other allergens (like pollen or dust), and overall health can also influence allergic reactions.\n\nIf you suspect you have pet allergies, it's a good idea to consult with an allergist for proper testing and advice on managing your symptoms.",
